Day three at Wimbledon proved a despairing one for home fans after both Emma Raducanu and Andy Murray crashed out at the second round stage. Raducanu, 19, went out in straight sets to the experienced Caroline Garcia whilst Murray, 35, was unable to cope with the serving of John Isner as he went down in four sets. But there will be renewed British hope on day four, despite Heather Watson having endured an agonising wait overnight after finishing Wednesday just one game away from the third round. JUST IN: Novak Djokovic confirms Boris Becker family prison trip after making Wimbledon gesture Court 1 (from 1pm) Jordan Thompson v Stefanos Tsitsipas (4) DON'T MISS:Cameron Norrie shows fighting spirit in five-set Wimbledon win over Jaume MunarNovak Djokovic confirms talks to join Federer, Nadal and Murray at Laver CupWimbledon fan grilled by security during Emma Raducanu clash on Centre Court Court 7 Alicja Rosolska/Erin Routliffe (11) v Irina-Camelia Begu/Anhelina Kalinina Court 8 Rajeev Ram/Joe Salisbury (1) v Daniel Altmaier/Carlos Taberner Juan Sebastian Cabal/Robert Farah (6) v Ugo Humbert/Adrian Mannarino Aliona Bolsova/Ingrid Neel v Latisha Chan/Samantha Stosur (12) Natela Dzalamidze/Aleksandra Krunic (13) v Anna-Lena Friedsam/Ann Li Court 9 Oceane Dodin/Tatjana Maria v Lyudmyla Kichenok/Jelena Ostapenko (4) Treat Huey/Franko Skugor v Nuno Borges/Francisco Cabral Monique Adamczak/Katarzyna Kawa v Alexa Guarachi/Andreja Klepac (7) Mackenzie McDonald/Katarzyna Kawa v John Peers/Filip Polasek (7) Court 10 Nicolas Mahut/Edouard Roger-Vasselin (12) v Francisco Cerundolo/Tomas Martin Etcheverry Ulrikke Eikeri/Astra Sharma v Alison Riske-Amritraj/CoCo Vandeweghe Kaitlyn Christian/Panna Udvardy v Nicole Melichar-Martinez/Ellen Perez (10) Julio Peralta/Alejandro Tabilo v Jonny O'Mara/Ken Skupski Court 11 Oksana Kalashnikova/Katarzyna Piter v Marie Bouzkova/Tereza Mihalikova (16) Radu Albot/Nikoloz Basilashvili v Alexander Bublik/Jiri Vesely Catherine Harrison/Sabrina Santama